{"eventId":"evt_gdpr_001","eventType":"claim_first_seen","claimId":"clm_gdpr_001","fromRevisionId":1280000301,"toRevisionId":1280000302,"section":"Summary","before":"","after":"The General Data Protection Regulation (GDPR) is a European Union regulation on data protection and privacy that took effect on May 25, 2018. It replaced the 1995 Data Protection Directive (Directive 95/46/EC) and introduced harmonized data protection rules across all EU member states.","deterministicFacts":[{"fact":"The foundational summary claim establishing the GDPR's effective date and its relationship to the 1995 Directive first appeared in this revision.","detail":"Added with citation to Regulation (EU) 2016/679 and the European Commission's GDPR overview page."}],"modelInterpretation":{"semanticChange":"Established the basic factual framework for the article.","confidence":0.97,"discussionType":"legislative_update"},"layer":"observed","timestamp":"2024-01-22T10:30:15Z"}
{"eventId":"evt_gdpr_002","eventType":"claim_reworded","claimId":"clm_gdpr_002","fromRevisionId":1280000303,"toRevisionId":1280000304,"section":"Legislative history","before":"The European Parliament adopted the GDPR in April 2016 after four years of negotiation.","after":"The GDPR had a six-year legislative journey: the European Commission proposed the data protection reform package in January 2012; the European Parliament adopted its position in March 2014; the Council of the European Union reached a general approach in June 2015; trilogue negotiations between the Commission, Parliament, and Council concluded in December 2015; and the final text was adopted by the Parliament on April 14, 2016, and by the Council on April 8, 2016. A two-year implementation period followed, with enforcement beginning on May 25, 2018.","deterministicFacts":[{"fact":"The claim was expanded from a one-sentence summary to a six-stage chronological account with specific dates.","detail":"Each stage is sourced to the relevant EU institution's press release or official journal entry."},{"fact":"The two-year implementation period (2016-2018) was explicitly added with citation to Article 99 of the GDPR.","detail":"The two-year gap between adoption and enforcement is legally significant, as organizations had 24 months to achieve compliance."}],"modelInterpretation":{"semanticChange":"Transformed a minimal timeline into a detailed legislative chronology with institutional granularity.","confidence":0.92,"discussionType":"factual_clarification"},"layer":"observed","timestamp":"2024-02-14T12:10:30Z"}
{"eventId":"evt_gdpr_003","eventType":"citation_replaced","claimId":"clm_gdpr_003","fromRevisionId":1280000305,"toRevisionId":1280000306,"section":"Territorial scope","before":"The GDPR applies to any organization that processes the personal data of EU residents, regardless of where the organization is located. [42]","after":"Under Article 3, the GDPR applies to: (1) organizations established in the EU that process personal data, regardless of whether the processing takes place in the EU; (2) organizations not established in the EU that process the personal data of individuals in the EU when the processing relates to offering goods or services or monitoring behavior. This extraterritorial reach has been described as 'one of the most ambitious assertions of regulatory jurisdiction in modern data protection law' [42][55][56].","deterministicFacts":[{"fact":"Two new citations [55] and [56] were added: Bradford (2020), 'The Brussels Effect,' and the EDPB's 2019 Guidelines 3/2018 on territorial scope.","detail":"Bradford provides the analytical framework for understanding extraterritorial regulatory reach; the EDPB guidelines are the authoritative interpretive document."},{"fact":"The claim was restructured from a single-sentence paraphrase to an Article-by-Article specification.","detail":"The Article 3 parsing reflects the two-pronged establishment and targeting tests."}],"modelInterpretation":{"semanticChange":"Enhanced legal precision by replacing paraphrase with statutory structure and adding scholarly commentary on extraterritorial scope.","confidence":0.94,"policyDimension":"verifiability","discussionType":"citation_strengthening"},"layer":"observed","timestamp":"2024-03-10T15:45:20Z"}
{"eventId":"evt_gdpr_004","eventType":"talk_thread_opened","claimId":null,"fromRevisionId":1280000307,"toRevisionId":1280000308,"section":"Talk:General Data Protection Regulation","before":"","after":"The 'Enforcement' section currently lists fines chronologically by amount. Several editors have proposed reorganizing by legal basis instead: by Article 58(2) corrective powers (fines, reprimands, bans) vs. Article 83(4)-(6) fine categories (up to €10M vs. up to €20M or 4% of global turnover). A chronological list implies that enforcement is escalating, which could be editorial framing rather than a neutral presentation of the data.","deterministicFacts":[{"fact":"A new talk page thread titled 'NPOV: Enforcement section organization' was opened.","detail":"Started by user EUPrivacyLaw on 2024-04-05T11:22:18Z."},{"fact":"The thread challenges the chronological-by-amount organization as potentially implying an enforcement-escalation narrative.","detail":"The editor proposes legal-basis organization (Article 58 corrective powers vs. Article 83 fine categories) as more neutral."}],"modelInterpretation":{"semanticChange":"Opened a framing dispute about whether chronological-by-amount enforcement presentation violates structural neutrality.","confidence":0.72,"discussionType":"neutrality_dispute"},"layer":"observed","timestamp":"2024-04-05T11:22:18Z"}
{"eventId":"evt_gdpr_005","eventType":"claim_first_seen","claimId":"clm_gdpr_004","fromRevisionId":1280000309,"toRevisionId":1280000310,"section":"Enforcement","before":"","after":"The record GDPR fine as of 2024 is the €1.2 billion penalty imposed on Meta Platforms Ireland Limited by the Irish Data Protection Commission in May 2023 for unlawful transfers of personal data to the United States under Article 46(1).","deterministicFacts":[{"fact":"The Meta Ireland fine claim first appeared in this revision.","detail":"Added with citation to the Irish DPC's final decision (IN-20-2-1) and the EDPB's binding decision 1/2023."},{"fact":"The legal basis (Article 46(1) transfer violations) was specified.","detail":"This distinguishes the Meta fine from the earlier Amazon €746M fine under Article 6 (lawfulness of processing) and the WhatsApp €225M fine under Articles 12-14 (transparency)."}],"modelInterpretation":{"semanticChange":"Introduced the largest GDPR enforcement action with precise legal characterization.","confidence":0.93,"discussionType":"enforcement_update"},"layer":"observed","timestamp":"2024-05-08T16:30:45Z"}
{"eventId":"evt_gdpr_006","eventType":"section_reorganized","claimId":null,"fromRevisionId":1280000311,"toRevisionId":1280000312,"section":"Enforcement","before":"(Section organized as a chronological list of fines from 2018 to present)","after":"(Section reorganized into: 'Enforcement framework' with Fining Guidelines, 'Notable enforcement actions by legal basis', and 'Cross-border enforcement under the One-Stop-Shop mechanism')","deterministicFacts":[{"fact":"The Section was reorganized from a chronological fine list to a three-subsection legal framework structure.","detail":"The reorganization followed the talk page NPOV discussion and was adopted after 24 replies reached consensus."},{"fact":"The 'One-Stop-Shop mechanism' subsection was new, consolidating material previously scattered across the 'Territorial scope' and 'Supervisory authorities' sections.","detail":"This addresses a common criticism that the article did not adequately explain the lead-authority mechanism, which is the procedural backbone of cross-border enforcement."}],"modelInterpretation":{"semanticChange":"Structural reorganization from narrative chronology to legal framework, resolving the NPOV concern about escalation framing.","confidence":0.80,"discussionType":"structure_dispute"},"layer":"observed","timestamp":"2024-06-22T09:55:30Z"}
{"eventId":"evt_gdpr_007","eventType":"claim_softened","claimId":"clm_gdpr_005","fromRevisionId":1280000313,"toRevisionId":1280000314,"section":"Impact","before":"The GDPR has been a resounding success, with compliance rates exceeding 90% among large enterprises and the regulation serving as a model for data protection laws in over 120 countries.","after":"The GDPR's impact has been significant but mixed. Compliance rates among large enterprises are estimated at 67-90% depending on the survey methodology and criterion measured, with small and medium enterprises reporting lower compliance. The regulation has influenced data protection legislation in over 120 countries—a phenomenon described as the 'Brussels Effect'—though the extent of actual legal harmonization varies substantially by jurisdiction and sector.","deterministicFacts":[{"fact":"The 'resounding success' characterization was removed and replaced with 'significant but mixed'.","detail":"The edit cited a 2023 IAPP survey showing variable compliance rates and a 2022 European Commission review that identified enforcement inconsistency across member states."},{"fact":"The Brussels Effect concept was added with citation to Anu Bradford's work rather than claimed in wiki voice.","detail":"The 120-country claim was retained but attributed to the Brussels Effect literature rather than stated as objective fact."}],"modelInterpretation":{"semanticChange":"Replaced a promotional success narrative with a nuanced assessment citing methodological variation, enforcement inconsistency, and SME compliance gaps.","confidence":0.89,"policyDimension":"neutrality","discussionType":"evidence_weighing"},"layer":"model_interpretation","timestamp":"2024-08-15T14:10:25Z"}
{"eventId":"evt_gdpr_008","eventType":"revert_detected","claimId":"clm_gdpr_006","fromRevisionId":1280000315,"toRevisionId":1280000316,"section":"Impact","before":"The GDPR has imposed significant compliance costs on businesses, with some estimates placing the total cost of implementation for Fortune 500 companies at over $9 billion.","after":"The GDPR has imposed significant compliance costs on businesses, with some estimates placing the total cost of implementation for Fortune 500 companies at over $9 billion.","deterministicFacts":[{"fact":"Revision 1280000315 was an exact revert of revision 1280000314.","detail":"An editor had replaced the Fortune 500 compliance cost estimate with 'While the GDPR has been a costly regulatory burden that stifles innovation, with some estimates placing total compliance costs at over $200 billion globally.' The significantly higher figure was sourced to a think tank press release, not a peer-reviewed study. The revert was applied by moderator EuropeanPolicyEditor."},{"fact":"Edit summary: 'rv — replacing a sourced $9B estimate with an unsourced $200B press-release figure. WP:RS and WP:DUE require independent secondary sourcing.'"}],"modelInterpretation":{"semanticChange":"Restored a peer-reviewed compliance cost estimate after a much larger unsourced figure from an advocacy organization was substituted.","confidence":0.95,"policyDimension":"verifiability","discussionType":"edit_revert"},"layer":"observed","timestamp":"2024-10-05T11:30:40Z"}
{"eventId":"evt_gdpr_009","eventType":"claim_strengthened","claimId":"clm_gdpr_007","fromRevisionId":1280000317,"toRevisionId":1280000318,"section":"Adequacy decisions","before":"The European Commission has issued adequacy decisions for several countries, allowing the free flow of personal data to those jurisdictions.","after":"As of 2024, the European Commission has adopted adequacy decisions for 15 countries and territories under Article 45 of the GDPR, including Japan (2019), the United Kingdom (2021, post-Brexit), South Korea (2021), and the EU-US Data Privacy Framework (2023). Adequacy decisions are subject to periodic review: the first review of the Japan decision was completed in 2023, and the UK adequacy decision includes a 'sunset clause' requiring re-approval by June 2025.","deterministicFacts":[{"fact":"The claim was expanded from a general statement to a countable list with specific dates and the sunset provision for the UK.","detail":"The 15-country figure is per the European Commission's adequacy decisions registry. The UK sunset clause is specified in the EU-UK Trade and Cooperation Agreement."},{"fact":"The periodic review mechanism was explained with the Japan (2023) and UK (2025) examples.","detail":"This detail is legally significant because adequacy decisions are not permanent; the framework explicitly requires periodic reassessment."}],"modelInterpretation":{"semanticChange":"Enhanced from a vague overview to a specific enumeration with temporal validity constraints.","confidence":0.90,"discussionType":"data_update"},"layer":"observed","timestamp":"2024-11-20T09:40:55Z"}
